Short answer: sometimes — but not always, and context matters.

More fully:
- Do unions drive up costs? Unions typically raise wages and benefits for their members (the “union wage premium”). In the US and many other countries empirical studies commonly find a premium on the order of roughly 10–20% historically, though it varies by sector, time period and country. Higher labor costs can raise firms’ unit costs in the short run. But that is only part of the picture: unions also reduce turnover, improve safety and working conditions, encourage training, and can raise worker morale and effort — all of which can raise productivity and partially or wholly offset higher wages. How much costs rise for a particular firm depends on bargaining power, product market competition, firm adjustments (price increases, lower profits, investment changes), and whether unions bargain over productivity-enhancing policies as well as pay.

- Do unions protect underperformers? Unions often negotiate job protections, grievance procedures, and due-process rights, which can make firing more difficult. That can make it harder to remove chronically low-performing employees in some cases. But evidence is mixed: many unions and collective agreements also encourage formal performance management, training, and redeployment rather than simple dismissal. Some research finds modest adverse effects on measured productivity from strict job protection, while other studies find little or no negative effect once you account for improved recruitment, lower turnover, and firm–union cooperation. In short, unions can make dismissals harder, but they also create incentives and mechanisms to address poor performance in other ways.

- Do unions reduce economic competitiveness? It depends on the market and the institutional setup. If unions push wages above what firms can sustain and firms face strong international competition, that can harm competitiveness, lead to job losses, or force offshoring. But in many advanced economies with coordinated bargaining (wage-setting tied to productivity across sectors), unions have helped sustain stable labor relations, invest in training, and limit wage inequality — outcomes that can preserve or even strengthen long‑run competitiveness. Moreover, in labor markets with employer monopsony power (limited hiring competition), unions can raise wages without large employment losses and can increase overall economic efficiency by correcting bargaining imbalances.

Bottom line: unions are neither purely “cost-raising” nor purely “productivity-enhancing.” Their net effect depends on:
- the bargaining framework (centralized vs decentralized);
- product‑market competition and openness to trade;
- the degree of employer monopsony power;
- whether unions bargain only over wages or over work rules, training, productivity and flexibility as well;
- firm responses (price increases, reduced margins, changed investment, productivity improvements).

If you want, I can: summarize key academic studies, show evidence for a particular country or industry, or outline policy designs (e.g., flexible collective bargaining, performance-based pay within unions, active labor-market policies) that aim to capture the benefits of unions while mitigating potential downsides.
